Krasnopyorov and Fadejeva: Raising the minimum wage - a wonderstick or a brake for the economy?
The question of raising the minimum wage in public discussions is almost the status of a sacred cow: either support for the raising, or mention any non-expressive, general phrases.
Taking into account the significant increase in the risk of economic stagnation (we barely avoided a technical recession), we think it is important to stress that raising the minimum wage is not a miracle that will reduce income inequality with one hint, will bring Latvian wages closer to the Western European level and will fill the state budget.
On the contrary, raising the minimum wage too much does more harm than good, because raising it reduces the competitiveness and employment of businesses, especially in sectors and regions with low incomes.
At first glance, it seems that despite several increases in the minimum wage in the post-crisis period, the minimum wage in Latvia is not so high that raising tens of euros a year would significantly weaken the competitiveness of companies - only 370 euros, while in some European Union (EU) countries the minimum wage is about one and a half thousand.
However, a different picture can be seen if we compare it with the average wage in the country (%): the minimum wage in Latvia (44%) exceeds the EU average.
Since the share of minimum wage recipients in Latvia is significantly higher than in neighbouring countries (in Latvia - 17%, Lithuania - 11%, Estonia - 6%[1]), a similar increase in minimum wage is binding for most companies.
According to the results of the survey of the companies of Latvijas Banka, one in five Latvian companies replied that as the minimum wage increased at the beginning of 2014, it was important or very important to increase the prices of products.
This means that, firstly, the rise in the minimum wage was partly financed by consumers (i.e., Latvian residents); secondly, raising prices meant loss of competitiveness for several companies both in the domestic market and abroad (i.e., increased imports and limited exports were promoted).
Due to the weaker competitiveness and shrinking production volumes, it was important for almost one in fifteen Latvian companies to lay off employees (which means more unemployment and emigration).
In addition, almost every eleventh company responded that it was important for him to limit recruitment of new employees due to raising the minimum wage.
It is worth remembering that in 2011-2013 the minimum wage in Latvia did not change.
Therefore, even if one in five companies noted productivity improvement as important when assessing the 2014 minimum wage increase, it does not mean that a similar result could be expected in 2017 (fourth increase of the minimum wage in a row could exhaust the possibilities of raising productivity).
Another important result is that, due to the rise in the minimum wage, it was important for several companies to increase the remuneration of employees who earn more than the minimum wage.
Thus, the impact of the minimum wage was significant even for those companies where the minimum wage was not received by any of the employees.
In recent years, the rise in minimum wages in all three Baltic countries exceeded that in nominal productivity (real productivity + inflation).
Thus, further increases in the minimum wage that are not justified by productivity growth (even despite the overall rather low level in euro terms) will have a negative impact on the competitiveness and employment of enterprises.
When assessing the justification for raising the minimum wage, it is not enough to analyse the average indicators of the economy.
It should also be examined whether raising the minimum wage is "tolerable" in sectors and regions where the minimum wage is most frequently used.
The results of Latvijas Banka's survey show that the concentration of employees with minimum wages is highest in small enterprises (the number of employees is from 10 to 19; 25%).
At the end of 2013, the share of employees with minimum wages was higher (16% and 19%, respectively) than in trade (15%), construction (11%) and financial and insurance sectors (2%).
On the other hand, for Latgale, where the minimum wage is 64% of the average wage (and more than two thirds of the average wage in the private sector), its further rise may be more damaging by reducing labour demand (i.e., maintaining already high unemployment) and promoting the sustainability of the shadow economy.
Some signs show that the large minimum wage rises (up 27%) implemented in 2014-2015 have slowed down the development of Latgale.
For example, Latgale is the only region in Latvia where unemployment in 2015 was higher than in 2013.
It should be noted that Estonia and Lithuania do not have any regions that would lag so much behind in terms of average wages from the rest of the country.
In Estonia, for example, the average wage in all regions is at least twice the national minimum wage.
In Lithuania, the lowest wages are in the Taurage region, but also there the minimum wage was 54% of the average wage in 2015 (after two sharp increases in the minimum wage in 2016, this indicator could reach 58%).
The call for raising the minimum wage up to 68% of the average wage in the country (see, for example, here) from time to time is lacking in economic justification and cannot be implemented in the short or long term.
First, such a high number of the average salary or even standing so close to it does not exist in any EU country.
Secondly, it would mean raising the minimum wage above the average wage in several sectors of the economy (which would mean bankruptcy and mass redundancies of companies in these sectors), for example, in the production of clothing, leather goods, fish processing, catering services, as well as in veterinary services; moreover, it is more than the current average wage in the private sector of Latgale.
Raising the minimum wage from January 2017 to 400-410 euros per month, as currently offered by the Ministry of Welfare, would make the minimum wage in Latvia (% of the average wage) one of the highest in the EU.
If nominal productivity increases by 4% and the minimum wage at least twice as fast, this has clear negative consequences for business competitiveness and employment.
This will be most common in those sectors and regions where the current minimum wage is often used, for example, in Latgale.
The fact that we cannot afford a significant increase in the minimum wage at the moment means that other mechanisms should be used to support low wage earners.
Immediate effect can be achieved by travelling with a personal income tax-free minimum (within the limits of budget possibilities).
Inadequate levels of education, inadequate education and poor quality of the education received, as well as poor health (which often occurs without going to the doctor because of the cost of medical services and long queues) are among the real causes of income inequality.
