The signs of unrest in Ukraine prompt the question: What does Vladimir Putin think?
The truth of these claims has been established.
Ukraine denies them, while the US and the European Union claim that Russia has not provided any evidence.
An open analysis group, the Digital Forensic Research Lab, has identified some signs of Saturday's shooting, but quite a few to be able to thwart Moscow's big plans.
Russia is known for distorting events or misinterpreting events for political purposes, especially in the context of the ongoing conflict in Ukraine.
This does not mean, however, that all Russian claims are unfounded.
The members of the Ukrainian resistance last year damaged the electricity pylons that supplied power to the Crimea, and some of them are also involved in criminal activities and human rights violations.
The attempted attack in Crimea is still a matter of concern, although there is little reason to suspect that the Ukrainian government would sponsor a scenario of such events.
Whatever has happened, the images found by open source analysts show that Russia has been increasing its military presence since at least last Saturday - before the expected attack occurred.
They show heavy weapon convoys moving through the peninsula, including shore defence missile systems.
Disruptively familiar Russian escalation
Separately, reports indicate that Russian forces in Crimea had already planned a rotation around this time, which could help explain the activity, although it would be a very big coincidence that it simply happened in one of the most tense times since the annexation in 2014.
Whatever has become known over the weekend, Mr Putin has undoubtedly turned even more to Ukraine in his statements, choosing to use this episode, however real, for whatever greater purpose.
Analysts point to worrying parallels with the way Russia dealt with Ukraine just before previous military actions.
In February 2014, with similar speeches and military manoeuvres, a cover was provided for Crimean volunteer members of the resistance forces to take up the peninsula, still controlled by Ukraine at the time, only to discover that, in fact, they were Russian special units that started the military occupation.
That August, when Russian-backed separatists failed in Eastern Ukraine, Putin deployed forces along the border, warning that they might be needed for the "protection" of those ethnic Russian civilians in Ukraine that he said were being attacked.
He arranged for a convoy of aid to the region, which, according to NATO, was only a cover for Russian invasion forces.
What does Mr. Putin plan to do in Crimea?
Some have speculated whether Moscow alone is planning another military intervention.
The fighting in Eastern Ukraine has escalated, as it did before the invasion in August 2014.
But this apparent parallel could be the point at which the fear of military action is supposed to be introduced, and not of actual action, which will give Putin a trump card, both in his relations with Ukraine and with the Western countries.
Mark Galeoti, a professor at the University of Nuyorka who studies Russia, pointed out that Crimea would have little importance as a point from which to start military actions against Eastern Ukraine, which borders on the land part of Russia, rather than Crimea, and that the rest of the country is better protected.
"There is quite a small chance if the Russians are really planning some large-scale offensive," Mr Galeoti said.
Rather, "we can observe a classic Russian strategy of creating a squeeze."
International peace talks on Ukraine, once a mechanism with which Putin imposed contacts with Western leaders who ignored him because of the annexation of Crimea, are increasingly seen as unsuccessful and irrelevant.
By promising that there is a danger that the conflict may erupt again, Putin gives the conversation a new meaning: to get him off the edge of the abyss.
"It's a standard Putin tactic - he wants to try and start from a position of strength," Galeoti said of the next peace talks scheduled for early September.
"And the only strength is to say, 'If I wanted to, I could make everything much, much worse.'"
Reach an agreement with the West
Putin also said this week that during the Crimean tensions it was of little importance to continue negotiations, forcing other parties to convince him to return to the negotiating table and get to the centre of the process.
What does it actually give him?
First, it allows Russia to further establish itself as a world power, even though its economy is smaller than that of Australia.
Secondly, it positions Moscow as the one who holds the right of veto over Ukraine's sovereignty, keeping the country under Russian control to some extent.
This may also benefit Putin's long-held hopes of a large-scale agreement with the United States that would resolve their disputes on the Ukraine-Syria issue, with Moscow favourable terms, naturally - also ending Western sanctions against Russia.
Putin hints at this goal since the country's economic situation deteriorated in 2014, has made numerous statements, mainly due to the country's declining export value of oil and gas.
Since the invasion of Syria last autumn, he has repeatedly called on Western powers to join him in the great coalition to fight extremists.
However, Russian leaders may feel they would need to secure such an agreement before January, when President Obama's term expires.
Russian officials basically believe that Hillary Clinton, who is more hostile to Moscow, will be the next president.
Donald J. Trump, though noticeably friendly to Russia, is still considered unpredictable.
Obama, on the other hand, is seen as one who "seeks solutions rather than conflicts," Galeoti said.
So it makes sense to close the option window to get something done quickly.
Meanwhile, if a large-scale agreement cannot be reached, Putin seems satisfied with the preservation of Russia's weak neighbour, mentioning what will happen next.
