Religion must become fashionable or go into oblivion
In the United States, Hillary Clinton has recently been nominated as her presidential candidate by the Democrat Party.
If the results of the latest polls also prove true in the election itself, America will inaugurate its first president, a woman, in January.
Last week, across the ocean, British Prime Minister Theresa May discussed Britain's withdrawal from Europe with German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Women brought up in Western society are brought up in such a way as to realize that through education, ambition, and hard work, they can be competent and successful in any field of professional activity.
And nowadays, young girls can target a number of existing role models by acting in the top leadership field.
So, is the long and hard fight for women's equality finally over?
Hillary Clinton is ready to become President of the United States at any moment, yet in the field of religion, women's leadership is still a contentious issue.
Okay, not completely.
In the religious field, women's leadership is still a controversial issue.
Last week, Pope Francis announced the creation of a new commission to assess whether women should be consecrated in deacons in the Catholic Church.
The Anglican Church consecrated Libya Lane as the first woman-bishop in January 2015, but it was only after a failed attempt in 2012.
While in the Reform Judaism movement women have been ordained in the rabbinical order since the early 1970s and in the conservative movement since the early 1980s, in Orthodox Judaism the concept of female rabbi still has a very fierce resistance.
In November 2015, the American Council of Orthodox Rabbis, in its third attempt to stem the growing wave of support for the rabbinic appointment of Orthodox women, published a rather harsh message that the concept of a female rabbi was contrary to the law.
Not without irony, when Hillary Clinton was nominated as Democrat presidential nominee, a group of America's leading Orthodox rabbis, who oppose the ordination of women, launched a series of "discussions" on this controversial issue.
Why is there such a difference between secular and sacred?
Orthodox Judaism, like most other religions, seeks stability in what it considers to be enduring traditional values.
It manifests itself in the ability to resist pressure to adapt to a changing society.
Those who are against ordination of women do so on the grounds that it is not "traditional."
However, being overtaken by the preservation of traditions in this way has its price.
And the price of such one-sided thinking can paradoxically undermine the tradition in itself by depriving the traditional community of the oxygen it needs to sustain life.
In the book "The Firearms of August", in the military history of World War I, Barbara Tachman emphasizes the danger of prioritising tradition in what has come to be known as "the tragedy of red trousers."
By the start of World War I, when warring shifted from warring at close distances to heavier artillery being fired from further distance, it became advantageous to hide soldiers for as long as possible.
The British and German armies responded to these changes by changing their bright uniforms to boring greys and browns.
French soldiers, however, still wore the same red hats and pants, which made them easy targets.
The proposal by the French Minister of War Adolphe Mesimeu that the armies under his command might act in a similar manner was met with ridicule and resistance.
The red pants reflected the pride and prestige of the army, and the military traditionalists were not prepared to give it up.
Speaking in parliament, former Minister of War Affairs Eugene Etienne spoke on behalf of France.
"Can you give up the red pants?" he exclaimed.
Never!
"That inexpressive and idiotic appendix to the most obvious of all colors," Messimy later wrote, "there had to be evil consequences."
Faith leaders who fight for the inclusion of women in leading religious roles could fall into the same trap.
Focusing solely on the "traditional" in religion rather than asking the important question, "What changes are needed for religion to flourish?" they risk losing about 50 percent of their followers.
They also deprive the whole community of the talent, skills and enthusiasm that women would otherwise bring.
To insist that men continue to wear trousers when it comes to religion may be traditional, but as the destruction of red trousers shows, it may not be worth it.
Dina Breiver is a founding member of JOFA (Women's Orthodox Feminist Association) in Great Britain and a student of orthodox rabbinicism at Yeshiwat Maharat in New York City.
