On Thursday, during a meeting with China's foreign minister Wang Yi, Ugandan President Yoveri Museveni thanked China for its long-standing Ugandan development support and expressed hope for closer cooperation.
Museveni said that China was an old friend of Uganda and Africa who supported the liberation of the African continent from colonialism and later supported the economic and social development of Africa.
The President mentioned the construction of the Tanzanian-Zambia Railway in the 1970s as evidence of China's generous support, which was given even when China itself was not particularly prosperous.
Museveni said that China has pursued multilateral cooperation with Uganda, both through investment in infrastructure and business and cultural exchanges, and added that this type of cooperation contributes to Uganda's long-term development more than simply financial assistance provided.
He hopes that China will be able to engage in various ways in the development of Uganda's infrastructure and the construction of industrial parks.
He also calls on the Chinese to invest more in Uganda and travel around it.
Wang Yi commended Uganda's performance in the areas of industrialization and agricultural modernization and added that China would continue to be the most trusted and ideal partner for Uganda.
Wang stated that China was willing to do whatever it could to help implement Uganda's economic and social development, and added that China-Uganda cooperation was genuine and free of any political considerations, as it was based on a high level of political credibility and time-tested friendship.
He said that China could strengthen cooperation with Uganda in the construction of infrastructure and industrial parks, as well as supporting the development of the energy and agricultural industries of this East African nation.
